 England, United Kingdom","Rivenhall, Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Rivenhall, Essex, England, United Kingdom","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Newinden, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Gosfield, Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom","High Easter, , Essex, England":"High Easter, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gates","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Gate</b> with plural or excrescent <i>-s</i>. The English surname <i>Gate</i> has three possible origins: (i) a topographic name from Middle English <i>gate</i> ‘gate’ (Old English <i>geat</i>, dative plural <i>gatum</i>), denoting someone who lived by a gate or set of gates (possibly sometimes an occupational name for a gate keeper; compre Yates); (ii) in northern England, the East Midlands, and East Anglia, a topographic name from Middle English <i>gate</i> ‘street, road, path’ (Old Norse <i>gata</i>) for someone who lived by a road (compare   Street  ); (iii) a nickname meaning ‘goat’, from northern Middle English <i>gate</i>, <i>gait</i> (Old English <i>gāt</i>, Old Norse <i>geitr</i>).","Americanized form of German <b>Götz</b> (see   Goetz  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of French <b>Barrière</b> (see   Barriere  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Street","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>stret(e)</i> ‘street, Roman road’ (Old English <i>strǣt</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in the main street of a village or town or by a Roman road, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Street (Kent, Herefordshire, Somerset), Street on the Fosse (Somerset), Strete in Blackawton (Devon), Strete Raleigh in Whimple (Devon), or Streat (Sussex). In the Middle Ages the word at first denoted a Roman road but later also came to denote the main street in a town or village.","Americanized form (translation into English) of Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Strasser   and a number of other surnames with similar meaning.","Americanized form of Jewish (from Morocco) <b>Chetrit</b>: perhaps from the Arabic verbal root <i>shṭr</i> ‘to become skillful, dexterous, astute’. The exact origin of the suffix <i>–it</i> is unclear."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Wesley","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the surname of the founder of the Methodist Church,  John Wesley  (  1703–91 ), and his brother  Charles  (  1707–88 ), who was also influential in the movement. Their family must have come originally from one or other of the various places in England called <i>Westley</i>, the ‘western wood, clearing, or meadow’. The given name was at first confined to members of the Methodist Church, but is now widely used without reference to its religious connotations."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Wesley Gates I was born in 1278, in Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir Thomas Gates, was 18 and his mother, Mrs. Thomas Gates, was 14. He married Mrs. John Gates before 1300, in Gosfield, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1378, in his hometown, at the age of 100."},"et":{"1278–1378":"1278–1378","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1300–1327":"1300–1327","1302–1337":"1302–1337","1260–1360":"1260–1360","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","before 1300":"enne 1300","1264":"1264","1285":"1285","1360":"1360","1260":"1260","1305":"1305","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1302":"1302","1378":"1378","1278":"1278","1300":"1300","before1278":"enne 1278","1276":"1276","Gosfield ,Essex, England":"Gosfield, Essex, Inglismaa, 